<span id="vi.ii.vii"></span>

<span id="vi.ii.vii-p1"></span> <span class="c1"><span
id="vi.ii.vii-p1.1"></span>VI.—Liturgical.</span>

<span id="vi.ii.vii-p2"></span>It is beyond the scope of the present
work to discuss at length the history and relation of the extant
Liturgies, which go by the name of St. Basil.  St. Basil’s precise share
in their composition, as we possess them, must be conjectural.

<span id="vi.ii.vii-p3"></span>(i)  The Liturgy, which St. Basil himself
used and gave to his clergy and monks, preserved the traditional form in
use in the archdiocese of Cæsarea. <span
id="fr_699"></span>[700](#fn_699.md)   It is mentioned in the xxxiind canon
of the council “in Trullo” of 692.  This is no doubt the basis of the
Greek Liturgy known as St. Basil’s, and used in the East as well as the
Liturgy of St. Chrysostom.  The form in use is contained in Neale’s
*Primitive Liturgies* (1875).  Dr. Swainson (*Greek Liturgies chiefly
from Oriental Sources*, p. 75) printed an edition of it from the
Barberini <span class="c14"><span id="vi.ii.vii-p4.1"></span>ms.</span>
in 1884.

<span id="vi.ii.vii-p5"></span>(ii)  There is an Alexandrine Liturgy in
Coptic, Arabic, and Greek form, called St. Basil’s, and used on fast
days by the Monophysites (Renaudot, *Lit. Orient. Collectio*, i. 154). 
This differs entirely from the first named.

<span id="vi.ii.vii-p6"></span>(iii)  Yet again there is a Syriac
Liturgy called St. Basil’s, translated by Masius, and given by Renaudot
in his second volume. <span id="fr_700"></span>[701](#fn_700.md)

